# Differentiate between Legibility and Readability.
Legibility refers to how easily individual characters (letters, numbers) can be distinguished from one another.
Readability refers to how easily a block of text can be read and understood as a whole, influenced by layout, line spacing, and font size.

# What is the “Rule of Thirds” in layout design?
The Rule of Thirds divides a page into a 3×3 grid. Important elements are placed along the grid lines or at their intersections to create a balanced, visually appealing, and engaging layout.

# Why should you limit the number of font families used on a website?
Limiting font families:
Improves visual consistency
Enhances readability
Reduces loading time
Usually, 2–3 font families are sufficient for a clean and professional design.

# Define “Responsive Web Design.”
Responsive Web Design is an approach where a website automatically adapts its layout, images, and content to fit different screen sizes and devices such as mobiles, tablets, and desktops.

long ans 
# Explain the “F-Pattern” of scanning and how it influences content placement on a web page.
The F-Pattern describes how users typically scan web pages:
First, they scan horizontally across the top
Then, a shorter horizontal scan below
Finally, a vertical scan down the left side
Design implications:
Place important content and headings at the top
Align key information along the left side
Use bold headings and bullet points to catch attention

# Discuss the psychological impact of colors in web design. Give examples of Blue, Red, and Green.
Colors influence user emotions and behavior:
Blue: Represents trust, calmness, and professionalism
Used in: Corporate websites, banks, social media platforms
Red: Conveys urgency, energy, and excitement
Used in: Call-to-action buttons, sales, alerts
Green: Symbolizes growth, health, and nature
Used in: Environmental sites, health and wellness platforms, finance apps

# Explain the “60-30-10 Rule” regarding color balance on a website.
The 60-30-10 Rule is a guideline for creating a balanced color scheme:
60%: Primary color (background)
30%: Secondary color (sections or containers)
10%: Accent color (buttons, highlights, call-to-action)
This rule ensures visual harmony, prevents clutter, and guides user attention effectively.

