Here are clear, well-structured long answers (4 marks each) written in an exam-friendly style:

#. Importance of Image Optimization and File Formats (JPEG vs PNG)
Image optimization is crucial for improving website performance and user experience. Using high-resolution raw images directly from a camera greatly increases file size, which leads to slow page loading, higher bandwidth usage, and user abandonment.
Importance of Image Optimization:
Reduces image file size without noticeable loss of quality
Improves page load speed
Enhances SEO ranking
Saves server bandwidth and improves performance on mobile devices
File Formats:
JPEG (JPG):Uses lossy compression
Best for photographs and complex images
Smaller file size and faster loading
PNG:
Uses lossless compression
Supports transparency
Best for logos, icons, and images with sharp edges or text
Larger file size compared to JPEG
Conclusion:
Optimizing images by resizing them to required dimensions and choosing the correct format (JPEG for photos, PNG for graphics) significantly improves website speed and usability.

# Critique of Using Bright Yellow Background and Comic Sans for a Law Firm Website
A law firm website must convey trust, professionalism, and credibility. Using a bright yellow background with Comic Sans violates key principles of Color Theory and Typography.
Color Theory Issues:
Bright yellow is visually overwhelming and causes eye strain
It conveys playfulness and caution rather than seriousness
It reduces readability, especially for long text

Typography Issues:
Comic Sans is an informal, playful font
It lacks authority and professionalism
It damages the brand image of a law firm

Better Alternatives:
Colors: Navy blue, dark gray, or deep green for trust and stability
Fonts: Serif fonts (Times New Roman, Georgia) or professional sans-serif fonts (Roboto, Open Sans)
Design Outcome: A clean, calm, and credible interface that aligns with legal professionalism

# Missing Design Principle and Use of Media Queries / Fluid Grids
The missing design principle is Responsive Web Design.
A website that looks good on a laptop but fails on mobile devices provides a poor user experience due to unreadable text and horizontal scrolling.

How Media Queries Help:
Allow CSS to apply different styles based on screen size
Adjust font sizes, layouts, and spacing for mobile screens
Hide or stack elements appropriately

How Fluid Grids Help:
Use percentage-based widths instead of fixed pixels
Allow layouts to adapt smoothly to different screen sizes
Prevent horizontal scrolling
Conclusion:
By implementing media queries and fluid grids, the website becomes flexible, readable, and usable across all devices, improving accessibility and user satisfaction.
